  "text": "The informational benefits of interpersonal ties-based on friendship, respect, or trustare also highlighted by [CITATION_1] and Patterson and his collaborators [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Notably, Fiellin implies already in the early 1960s that legislative network structures affect information flow, when he suggests that informal groups facilitate communication across party and committee lines (1962, 82) . His observation touches on two important themes that would be picked up in later work: the importance of weak, cross-cutting ties for information exchange and the relationship between social networks and formal legislative institutions.",
